<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kuma</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I want to modify my ShowEQ source so that it will sound my system speaker a set number of times when an "Alert" mob is found.  I thought that adding a for loop around the call to the system speaker would do the trick, but alas it does not work.  It only sounds the system speaker one time no matter how many iterations it loops.  I was wondering if one of you may know what I am doing wrong...<P>From packet.cpp<P>   while (re)<BR>   {<BR>      if (re-&gt;regexp-&gt;match (oname) != -1)<BR>      {<BR>	 printf ("SPAWN!!!***%s***\n", oname);<P>	 // Gereric system beep for those without a soundcard<BR>	 //<BR>	 if (!showeq_params-&gt;spawnfilter_audio)<BR>	 {<BR>           for(int i=0;i&lt;9;i++){   // Added to sound the alarm more than once<BR>	     fprintf(stderr,"\a");<BR>         }<BR>	 }<BR>	 else<BR>	 {<BR>	    //plays a wav file<BR>	    system ("/usr/bin/esdplay spawn.wav &");<BR>	 }<BR>	 return 1;<BR>      }<BR>      re = re-&gt;next;<BR>   }<P><BR>Any help would be sincerely appreciated.<BR>[This message has been edited by Kuma (edited 12-28-2000).]<p>[This message has been edited by Kuma (edited 12-28-2000).]</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Gadianton</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Try increasing the i to something higher than 9.  Remember, outputting to stderr is an asynchronous operation so it's going to go through the 9 at computer speeds not waiting for the speaker to finish.  I'm guessing that the machine just dumps whatever bells are pending until the first is done.<P>That's actually a smart thing to have done.  I remember when programs would emit 20 beeps and it would annoy the crap out of everyone in the office because it would do every freaking beep.<P>I'm not sure, but I would think that this function would be handled at the BIOS level, though it could be the OS handling that.  I dunno.  Sadly, my need to make a living has migrated me into wimpy applications programming.  Forgive me oh gods of real languages!   <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.org/ubb/smile.gif"></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Pooly</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">There's a solution which doesn't involve any source code changes whatsoever. showeq.conf lets you specify the program to run for the sound alerts. Get a program which just makes a PC speaker beep and put that in your conf file. In case you don't have one,<P>beep.c:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">code:</font><HR><pre><BR>#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;<BR>#include &lt;ncurses.h&gt;<P>int main()<BR>    {<BR>    initscr();<BR>    beep();<BR>    endwin();<BR>    return(0);<BR>    }<BR></pre><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>cc -lncurses -o beep beep.c<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">EzSteve</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Actually, you can modify the code to generate multiple speaker beeps quite easily. You just need to put a delay loop inside your loop for the number of beeps. I don't recall how much of a delay you'll need, play with it.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">FrozenInTime</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">heh, learn something new everyday.  Now I don't have to bother with configuring my friend's laptop sound chipset, just make the damn thing beep at him.  Just curious though, do filters work in SEQ 2.5 and if so, I'm assuming they go in an alerts file.  so if I wanted to look for #Icetooth in the Great Divide I'm assuming that I'll have something like:<P>[alerts]<BR>cetooth<P>and it should go off if if finds that string anywhere in the mobs name?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Kuma</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Thanks for all the help!!! I got it working...now if I could just get that spawn to occur!</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Hassanchop</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I like the idea of writing the beep code, but being just a slow newbie here are the problems i am having with the beep.c code. First it said ncurses.h not found, so i went to the ncurses page and downloaded 5.2..followed instructions, did ./configure /make then /make intall. Stopped getting the ncurses.h not found but now get "undefined reference to 'initscr'" and the same with 'beep' and 'endwin'. What is missing or dose someone know where i can just download a compiled beep program? Thanks</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">ahminus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Add "#include &lt;qapplication.h&gt;" at the top of that source file, next to the other Qt includes and call QApplication::beep().<P>It's one line:<BR>QApplication::beep();<P><BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
